entry.title: [ChromeOS Flex] Add device policy for sending hw data
entry.content:
This adds a new device policy for managed ChromeOS Flex devices to

control whether detailed hardware component data can collected for

product improvement purposes. We'd like the administrator to be very

clear on what the data will be used for, and not piggy-back on other

policies that allow data collection intended for customer use.



This is Flex-only, sending hardware data, for product improvement.

Device policies should start with "Device", according to a comment in

src/chromium/src/components/policy/tools/syntax_check_policy_template_json.py

Boolean policies end with "Enabled" by convention? So our policy name:

`DeviceFlexHwDataForProductImprovementEnabled`.



Although docs/enterprise/add_new_policy.md says we need to add a

preference and register it in Local State, etc. that doesn't appear to

be necessary for Device policies.



Tested by copying the chrome_device_policy.proto to a cros_sdk, and

building libbrillo (with added accessors) against it, then using the new

accessors to check value.

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Avoid restart at kSemicolonToken
entry.content:
With the CSSNestingIdent feature enabled, we retry any failed

declaration as a nested style rule, relying on backing out quickly

from the failed declaration due to e.g. an unrecognized property.

However, for properties that *are* recognized, but contain invalid

values, we're currently doing unnecessary work. Consider a case like:



background: -webkit-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: -moz-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: -o-linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);

background: linear-gradient(... lots of tokens ...);



For each of the prefixed values, ConsumeDeclaration will tokenize

to the to capture the whole value as

a CSSParserTokenRange, and eventually fail to parse. We'll then

restart as a nested rule, which will ultimately skip to the same

again. We can avoid this by checking if we ended up

at the in the first round.



This works due to CL:4897802, which would instead stop at '{' when

it in fact *is* a valid nested rule.



Results for NestingIdentInvalidValue.html on my machine:



With this CL: avg ~57ms

Without this CL: avg ~119ms



Bug: 1427259

entry.title: SimpleCache: fix lifetime of AppStatusListener on Android.
entry.content:
Previously, NetworkContext would pass SimpleBackendImpl creation

a pointer to a status listener it owns. While NetworkContext

normally owns both the cache and the app status listener, the

cache backend creation is an asynchronous process, so if the

network context was destroyed before the cache creation was

complete, and ownership of fresh cache backend handed over to

NetworkContext, the backend could end up using a dangling

pointer to AppStatusListener.



This changes to pass in a getter RepeatingCallback instead,

which checks for NetworkContext destruction before returning

the pointer.



Re-enable some tests that were flaking because of this.

entry.title: [Track Stats] Remove support for non-gUM/gDM tracks.
entry.content:
In a defensive stance (in terms of implementer burdon), the track.stats

API was only defined for getUserMedia/getDisplayMedia-based sources.

- This is a shame, because video processing is gaining popularity and it

would be great to be able to know about frame counters for these

non-device tracks as well.



Based on implementation experience, this does seem unnecessary and I

filed https://github.com/w3c/mediacapture-extensions/issues/102, but

for now this API should only be applicable to "device"-backed tracks.



It's possible there could be more implementation burdon if it turns out

that other sources are able to drop frames early (meaning, before the

VideoTrackAdapter sees the frame), because if so we need to wire up the

OnFrameDropped callback to all source implementations. But for now my

understanding is that "early" OnFrameDropped is only applicable on

real-time devices and that supporting all types of tracks would have

been no extra effort.



But until we can confirm this and convince the WG, let's align with

the spec and throw an exception on non-device sources.

entry.title: Break up gen_root_store_inc dependency
entry.content:
* The dependency is conditionally added [here](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:net/BUILD.gn;l=1422?q=gen_root_store_inc%20path:net%20file:BUILD.gn&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc) guarded behind

`chrome_root_store_supported`, hence removing it from being an unconditional dependency should not affect any platform as `chrome_root_store_supported` is enabled for every platform as seen [here](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:net/features.gni;l=52?q=net%2Ffeatures.gni&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc) except fuchsia and Cronet.

* gen_root_store_inc generates ev-roots which is used by `ev_root_ca_metadata`, `ev_root_ca_metadata` is only used when the builtin cert verifier

is used which is not the case for Cronet as seen [here](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:net/cert/cert_verifier.cc;l=29;bpv=1;bpt=1). However,

it is used by fuchsia so I added the `gen_root_store_inc` dependency to fuchsia only builds.

* gen_root_store_inc generates the chrome root store that is used to certification verification.

This is not used by Cronet because Cronet is an android library, hence should not use its own root store.

* All of this is currently being compiled then stripped away by the linker for Cronet. It'd be much better if we don't compile this at all

to make sure it doesn't get included by mistake as seen [here](b/267749933).

entry.title: Simplify Autofill ML model executor + handler
entry.content:
The ML code is structured as follows:

- The AutofillModelExecutor is responsible for converting the model

input into a format that TFLite understand and converting the model

output back to something that Autofill understands.

- The AutofillMlPredictionModelHandler is responsible for retrieving

the model (e.g. from the server), loading it and asynchronously

calling the executor.



This CL makes some minor simplifications to both classes, which will

simplify the follow-up CLs:

- Defines AutofillModelExecutor::Model(Input|Output) and replaces all

hard coded instances of it. Follow-up CLs will change what the

input/output types are.

- Early return in AutofillMlPredictionModelHandler::

GetModelPredictionsForForm() when the model isn't available. This

way, follow-up CLs can assume that everything was initialized

correctly otherwise.

- Use the newish base::test::TestFuture<> instead of base::RunLoop in

the executor unit test.

entry.title: [text-spacing-trim] Use a Trie for `HanKerning::GetCharType`
entry.content:
Last a few rules of "Fullwidth Punctuation Collapsing"[1]

require characters in ASCII, such as U+0028[2]. This makes

optimizing `HanKerning::GetCharType` by early return more

difficult.



This patch moves the logic to the ICU Trie data structure,

built on the build time. The time needed should be almost the

same as getting one Unicode property.



This patch has no behavior changes.



[1] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-text-4/#fullwidth-collapsing

[2] https://util.unicode.org/UnicodeJsps/list-unicodeset.jsp?a=%5B%3Agc%3DPs%3A%5D%5B%3Agc%3DPe%3A%5D&g=&i=

entry.title: sensors: Add virtual sensor commands to browser_protocol.pdl and CDP implementation
entry.content:
Design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1JS2Wnyc9GiS_u1Ry3w4KsCyd51g8fm4RDEUcanZgzbM/edit?usp=sharing



This adds a few types and 3 new commands to the Emulation domain:

* getOverriddenSensorInformation(type: SensorType) -> { requestedSamplingFrequency: number }

* setSensorOverrideEnabled(enabled: boolean, type: SensorType, optional metadata: SensorMetadata)

* setSensorOverrideReadings(type: SensorType, reading: SensorReading)



Together, they allow us to implement the create/get/update/remove

virtual sensor WebDriver commands from the Automation section of the

Generic Sensor spec (the ChromeDriver bits will come later).



Most of the code has already been implemented elsewhere in content and

services. The CDP bits involve exposing the virtual sensor operations

from WebContentsSensorProviderProxy via an RAII object called

ScopedVirtualSensorForDevTools: since the entry point to the virtual

sensor operations is always CDP, this object is responsible for

automatically creating and removing virtual sensors while WCSPP takes

care of creating only one ScopedVirtualSensorForDevTools per sensor

type. This way, each EmulationHandler instance has its own set of

virtual sensors that are cleared when it is disabled, and other handlers

that exist at the same time are unable to create, interact with or

remove these virtual sensors.



[The increase in binary size for Fuchsia cannot be avoided, it all comes

mostly from the generated code for the new data in browser_protocol.pdl and

the new code in content::protocol::EmulationHandler]

entry.title: Move promise item attributes to the installed app
entry.content:
Improve interactions between promise app sync data and the target,

"promised" app sync data. Handles two scenarios:

1. New install - when the promise app is installed, copy all of

the promise app's sync item data to the target app's sync data.

2. For install from sync, in which case a target app will have a sync

item, "link" the promise app and the target app's sync items, so

updates from sync get applied to the promise app, and the promise

app updates from ash get applied to the target app.



To support the second case, add a map that links promise app IDs to the

target app IDs to AppListSyncableService. When handling sync updates,

and updates from the UI, AppListSyncableService makes sure that promise

app and the target app are updated together. The "linkage" is

established when ChromeShelfController, or AppServicePromiseAppBuilder

notice a promise app update - because it's used from more than one

place, request to link a promise app to an existing sync item can be

called multiple times (on subsequent calls, the old linked app ID will

get reused).



To support the first use case, add "installed" app ID field to the

PromiseAppUpdate, and on success, provided that the promise app was

not linked to an existing sync item, AppServicePromiseAppBuilder will

copy the promise app sync item attributes to the installed app sync

item.



This CL also adds a PromiseAppRemoved observer interface to

PromiseAppRegistryCache observer, so observers can act upon promise app

removal separately from its final update. This makes sure that

ChromeShelfController or AppServicePromiseAppBuilder don't remove

promise app sync data before the other one has had a chance to set the

target state on the installed item - both classes observer the same

event, and there was potential for ChromeShelfController to unpin the

promise app in response to promise app install completing before the

AppServicePromiseAppBuilder had a chance to copy the promise app pin

ordinal to the installed app.

entry.title: [Files F2] Refine rename/focus logic for directory tree container
entry.content:
* `insertBefore` in the directory tree container causes the tree item

to lose states like focus/rename, we need to restore them if needed.

* Add `renameItemWithKeyWhenRendered/focusItemWithKeyWhenRendered`

methods for the directory tree container to handle cases where we

want to rename/focus items which are not rendered yet.

* When a focused tree item is deleted, we need to update the focused

item to either currently selected item or item which will become

selected later, otherwise the focus will go back to BODY.

* Enable DirectoryTreeContextMenu browser tests with the new tree to

test all above changes.
